english:
  title: Preface to a Poem Sent to Han Kong, Provincial Inspector of Chungcheong
  author: Kwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the summer of the Bingzi year under the Hongwu era, when Han Kong, Vice Director of the Central Secretariat, was appointed Provincial Inspector of Chungcheong and prepared to depart, he asked me for words of counsel. This is like borrowing ears from the deaf and seeking direction from the blind. Yet bound by the old ties of friendship and the bonds of kinship, how could I remain silent? Thus I dare to offer these humble thoughts.

    The afflictions of the people are of three kinds, yet the methods of treating them differ. Those born of improper care can be healed with medicine and acupuncture. Those stemming from innate imbalance must be corrected through learning and study. Those arising from failures of governance cannot be remedied save by one possessed of both noble talent and proper cultivation. All three demand urgent attention, yet two concern only the welfare of individuals, while one touches the very order or chaos of the realm. The weight and urgency are thus clear.

    A mediocre physician cannot cure the disease, nor can a half-learned scholar restore the temperament. Even if one possesses talent, without proper learning, all one's actions will miss their mark. It is like examining a sickness without feeling the pulse, or prescribing medicine without following the formula—at worst, adding cold to cold and heat to heat. How could such an approach not go astray?

    Under the House of Wang, the rot of corrupt governance afflicted our people to the utmost extreme. Yet when our sovereign rose to power, he established order and rectified the boundaries. Thus our people's suffering was nine-tenths relieved. Upon ascending the throne, he dispensed benevolent rule, and the people's anguish dissolved. The fevered cooled, wounds healed, the fallen rose, and the famished grew fat. Yet still his heart aches that his reach is not broad enough and his aid not sufficient. Therefore, he selects capable administrators to govern and sends great ministers to oversee, desiring that even in the remote and distant places, not a single soul should lack their rightful place. Truly this is benevolence at its height and righteousness perfected.

    Our commissioner possesses a naturally compassionate nature and learning both sound and grand. His conduct is upright and conscientious, his affairs managed with precision and swift judgment. In official documents, his words are faithful; in matters of state, his decisions are sure and fitting. In both character and learning, he is abundantly endowed. Therefore, our sovereign, selecting from the officials of court, has conferred this commission upon him—entrusting him, as it were, with the eyes and ears to broaden perception and discern the people's afflictions. This is no mere external appointment.

    Alas, that the welfare of ten thousand people—the very order or chaos of the realm itself—should be entrusted to your hands for governance! How could you not revere this charge? How could you not labor with all your might? The teachings tell us: "Guard them as you would a newborn child." And: "If your seeking is sincere, though you may not always hit the mark, you will not go far astray." If with sincere heart you seek their good, and with empty mind you approach your work, warming the cold and refreshing the parched, transforming their groans into songs and raising the weary sick to long life—then above you shall not betray the throne, and below you shall not betray your learning.

    As for ledgers and treasuries, established law already provides. Why should more be said?
  footnotes:
    - 'The ''three afflictions'' are a metaphor for social disorders: those caused by poor administration (medical neglect), those stemming from nature (innate condition), and those caused by governance (policy failure).'
    - The reference to the House of Wang (王氏) concerns the fallen Goryeo dynasty, establishing the historical context of the Joseon restoration.
    - Kwon Geun employs the physician metaphor throughout—the remedy must match the diagnosis—to advise Han Kong on administrative wisdom.
    - '''As you would a newborn child'' (如保赤子) is a classical Confucian maxim found in Mencius, emphasizing the benevolent ruler''s protective care for the people.'
